entry.title: Implement resolving and computing of color records from interpolable
entry.content:
FontPalette



In CSSFontSelector, the binary tree of FontPalette values (representing

mix values) is already built. So we need to retrieve and apply values

from the @font-palette-values at-rules, just as it is done for the

non-animation case for custom palettes.



If there were problems retrieving data from the at-rules, for example

the current matching font-family does not match with the one in the

descriptor, we apply FontPalette that represents normal CSS value on

that leaf.



CSSFontSelector is also responsible for simplifying the tree. For

example, if at some point while traversing the tree we have the

situation where both of the endpoints of mix-palettes() operation are

equal, we can skip the mix-palettes node and use one of its children.



Then once we arrive in FontCustomPlatformData, we traverse the tree.

Once we reach the leaves we retrieve color records from the matching

font. From those we interpolate, scale or add two color lists on each

node of the tree.



Design doc:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S9JJfjmBtmOVYyP9AmdTFsKfWetU7drsc2v7VSDQXoI/edit?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-O21aXZY1z6MoClTB-cKmlw

Explainer: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1XMTrKH003KBOes6hxzI-3E7LTwp5YwFC-rnzoFpFrfw/edit?usp=sharing

entry.title: Implement mix value representation in FontPalette
entry.content:
Change FontPalette class to binary tree structure to represent

FontPalette mix value. Each node represents one of the following

operations: palette-mix, palette-add, palette-scale. The child notes represent FontPalettes that these operations apply to. [1]

entry.title: Don't keep Inactive Tabs VC in memory
entry.content:
This CL changes the lifecycle of InactiveTabsViewController: instead of

keeping it alive as long as the regular Tab Grid (i.e. forever), it's

created when presented, and destroyed when dismissed.

This is because a Tab Grid incurs a large memory cost due to the tab

snapshots that it displays. By destroying the Inactive Tabs VC when not

used, we ensure a lower memory footprint throughout the use of the app.



This CL regresses on one point: the scroll offset is no longer kept

between showings of the Inactive Tabs VC. Opened crbug.com/1448025 to

track.

entry.title: bindings: Remove [Serializable] from IDL dictionaries
entry.content:
[Serializable] is an annotation to indicate that platform objects

(instances of IDL interfaces) are serializable. [Serializable] is

not applicable to IDL dictionaries.

serializable by default unless it contains a non-serializable

platform object. And all the cases in this patch do not contain

any platform object. Hence, no need of [Serializable]

entry.content:
Plumbs a Connector's static interface name string into various dispatch

stack frames. These frames are common places for processes to crash when

an endpoint has been destroyed from the wrong thread while a dispatch

task is in flight for it.



By propagating a reference to the interface name through the call stack

it should be possible to pinpoint specific offending interfaces by

examining crash dumps.

entry.title: CrOS Settings: Lifetime unique settings changed metrics.
entry.content:
Setting up UMA for sending metrics at the end of a Settings session and

recording the number of unique Settings changed per each user over a

device's lifetime. We will be recording the data in a bucket histogram

named:

"ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime".



Bug= b/280480850

TEST=

Manual:

1. Open Settings

2. Change a Setting that we are recording the name of, such as

switching the toggle for Do Not Disturb.

3. Close the Settings app, open your browser and search

"chrome://histograms", then find the histogram

"ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime". There

will be one count added to the respective bucket. The bucket

represents the number of unique changes made over the device's

lifetime.

4. Repeat steps 1-3 with different Settings changed each time. The

histogram will each time record the correct number of accumulated

unique Settings changed.



1. DISPLAY=:20 out/Default/unit_tests

--gtest_filter="*PerSessionSettingsUserActionTrackerTest*"

2. DISPLAY=:20 out/Default/unit_tests
